 individual prometheus.Counter, prometheus.Gauge, and prometheus.Histogram fields that are instantiated in `newScrapeMetrics(reg prometheus.Registerer)` and registered via `reg.Register()` calls within error handling blocks.\n\n3. **Lazy registration**: Components like `storage/remote/queue_manager.go` define `queueManagerMetrics` and register metrics when needed using `reg.MustRegister()`\n\nThis approach keeps registration coupled with business logic and provides maximum flexibility for different initialization patterns across the codebase.\n\n## Grafana/grafana - promauto Automatic Registration\n\nGrafana uses the modern `promauto` library for automatic metric registration. The pattern is:\n\n1. **Registerer-based construction**: Metrics are created in functions taking `prometheus.Registerer` parameter (e.g., `NewSchedulerMetrics(r prometheus.Registerer)` in `pkg/services/ngalert/metrics/scheduler.go`)\n\n2. **Automatic registration via promauto**: Instead of manual registration, metrics are created with `promauto.With(r).NewCounter()`, `promauto.With(r).NewGauge()`, `promauto.With(r).NewHistogram()` which automatically registers them with the provided registerer\n\n3. **Struct-based metric grouping**: Related metrics are organized in structs (Scheduler, NotificationHistorian, RemoteAlertmanager) stored as fields, allowing cohesive metric lifecycle management\n\nExamples include `pkg/infra/metrics/metrics.go` (core metrics), `pkg/registry/apis/provisioning/jobs/metrics.go`, `pkg/services/ngalert/metrics/scheduler.go` (which uses promauto with Namespace and Subsystem organization), and `pkg/storage/unified/resource/bleve_index_metrics.go` (using native histogram buckets).\n\nGrafana's approach is most modern and declarative, with automatic registration reducing boilerplate and making the metric definition more concise than explicit registration calls."
