  "text": "Prometheus metrics are registered and exposed differently across the three repositories, reflecting their distinct architectural approaches:\n\n## Kubernetes/kubernetes - Custom KubeRegistry Wrapper\n\nKubernetes implements a sophisticated abstraction layer wrapping the Prometheus registry. The core is in `staging/src/k8s.io/component-base/metrics/registry.go`, which defines a custom `KubeRegistry` interface that wraps `prometheus.Registry`. This wrapper provides additional capabilities including:\n\n- Metric deprecation lifecycle management (StabilityLevel markers: ALPHA, BETA, STABLE)\n- Version-aware metric visibility (metrics can be hidden based on Kubernetes version)\n- Custom collectors via `StableCollector` interface\n- Meta-metrics tracking total registered/disabled/hidden metrics\n\nA global `legacyregistry` module (`staging/src/k8s.io/component-base/metrics/legacyregistry/registry.go`) provides module-level registration functions like `MustRegister()` and `RawMustRegister()`. Metrics are defined throughout the codebase (e.g., `pkg/kubelet/metrics/metrics.go`, `pkg/scheduler/metrics/metrics.go`, `pkg/proxy/metrics/metrics.go`) using Kubernetes-specific metric constructors and are registered via `legacyregistry.MustRegister()` in sync.Once-protected functions to ensure single registration.\n\n## Prometheus/prometheus - Direct Native Registry\n\nPrometheus uses the standard Prometheus client library registry directly without wrapper abstractions. Metrics are created and registered via:\n\n1. **Init-time registration**: Global metrics defined in var blocks are registered in init() functions using `prometheus.MustRegister()` (e.g., `template/template.go` with `templateTextExpansionFailures` and `templateTextExpansionTotal`)\n\n2. **Function-based registration**: Many components encapsulate metrics in structs with a constructor function that takes a `prometheus.Registerer` parameter. For example, `scrape/metrics.go` defines `scrapeMetrics` struct with individual prometheus.Counter, prometheus.Gauge, and prometheus.Histogram fields that are instantiated in `newScrapeMetrics(reg prometheus.Registerer)` and registered via `reg.Register()` calls within error handling blocks.\n\n3. **Lazy registration**: Components like `storage/remote/queue_manager.go` define `queueManagerMetrics` and register metrics when needed using `reg.MustRegister()`\n\nThis approach keeps registration coupled with business logic and provides maximum flexibility for different initialization patterns across the codebase.\n\n## Grafana/grafana - promauto Automatic Registration\n\nGrafana uses the modern `promauto` library for automatic metric registration. The pattern is:\n\n1. **Registerer-based construction**: Metrics are created in functions taking `prometheus.Registerer` parameter (e.g., `NewSchedulerMetrics(r prometheus.Registerer)` in `pkg/services/ngalert/metrics/scheduler.go`)\n\n2. **Automatic registration via promauto**: Instead of manual registration, metrics are created with `promauto.With(r).NewCounter()`, `promauto.With(r).NewGauge()`, `promauto.With(r).NewHistogram()` which automatically registers them with the provided registerer\n\n3. **Struct-based metric grouping**: Related metrics are organized in structs (Scheduler, NotificationHistorian, RemoteAlertmanager) stored as fields, allowing cohesive metric lifecycle management\n\nExamples include `pkg/infra/metrics/metrics.go` (core metrics), `pkg/registry/apis/provisioning/jobs/metrics.go`, `pkg/services/ngalert/metrics/scheduler.go` (which uses promauto with Namespace and Subsystem organization), and `pkg/storage/unified/resource/bleve_index_metrics.go` (using native histogram buckets).\n\nGrafana's approach is most modern and declarative, with automatic registration reducing boilerplate and making the metric definition more concise than explicit registration calls."
